In reality, (and unfortunately), there isn't a definitive answer to this question because swallows don't typically fly in a vacuum where terminal velocity would apply.

Terminal velocity refers to the maximum speed an object can reach as it falls through a fluid (like air or water) when the force of gravity pulling it down is balanced by the frictional force pushing it back up.

Keep in mind that this estimate was made assuming a swallow in a spread-wing glide, to maximize its surface area and thus slow down its descent as much as possible.
